			"description": "## Authentication\n\nAPI request requires authentication to set permissions and privileges to enable access to authorized users. Authentication helps to identify the user license that is responsible for making the request. Authentication is provided by access tokens and refresh tokens\n\n#### Role based access tokens?\n\nEach license has two tokens:\n\n- `Employer access token` - allows you to manage your job postings, scheduled interviews, salary expectations, set probation periods and more. The access token should never be shared as it gives full access to your account.\n    \n- `Applicant access token` - allows applicant to apply to posted jobs, query endpoint requests to jobs\n    \n\n## Authentication example\n\nInclude this HTTP header for each API request:\n\n`Authorization: Bearer ${ACCESS_TOKEN}`[.](https://app.chatbot.com/settings/developers)\n\n## Error handling\n\nIn general, we use a consistent standard for error messages, that is, errors are returned using standard HTTP error code syntax. For example, most REST APIs include fields like `error`, `message`, `code` (an internal error code specific to your application), and sometimes `details` for additional information\n\n### HTTP status codes summary\n\n- 2xx – **The request indicate success. T**_he status response code from the server for successful HTTP requests_\n    \n- `4xx` – **Client Error**. The server cannot or will not process the request due to something that is perceived to be a client error e.g deceptive request routing\n    \n- `5xx` – **Server Error**. The request method is not supported by the server and cannot be handled"
